You are producing a faithful distillation of ONE chapter of a non-fiction book. The reader will read your output INSTEAD of the source. Your job is to preserve the load-bearing content at approximately {{ compression_pct }}% of the original length, written in clean prose.

This is not a summary. This is a distillation — the same book, compressed.

The SPINE below lists every element that MUST appear in your output. You may not skip anything on the spine. You may add connective tissue, transitions, and brief paraphrase to make the prose read well, but you may not introduce new concepts or examples not in the spine.

VOICE: Match the author's voice as shown in the voice sample. Match their register, sentence rhythm, and vocabulary. A reader should not notice the distillation is machine-generated.

STRUCTURE:
- Follow the argumentative_moves in order. They are the chapter's backbone.
- Open with a clear statement of the thesis (you may rephrase but do not soften).
- Integrate each framework at the point the author introduces it.
- Weave each key_example into the argument it supports.
- Close where the chapter closes — do not add a "summary of this chapter" coda.

RULES:
1. NO bullet lists, NO headers within the chapter text. Flowing prose only. Unless the source itself is structured as a list (e.g., "seven habits"), in which case mirror the structure.
2. NO meta-commentary. No "this chapter argues..." or "the author shows...". Just write in the author's voice.
3. NO filler. No "importantly,", "notably,", "it is worth noting,". Cut throat-clearing.
4. Inline citations: at the end of each paragraph, append the paragraph_ids from which the content was drawn, in the format [p:id1, p:id2]. These become clickable anchors in Obsidian.
5. TARGET LENGTH: {{ target_words }} words (±15%). This is not optional. Write tight.

